IDENTIFY the lesser omentum, and its subdivisions, the hepatogastric     and hepatoduodenal ligaments. Note that it extends from the lesser curvature of the stomach to the visceral surface of the liver.

The lesser omentum is a derivative of the ventral mesentery, and as such, connects the visceral peritoneum of the stomach with that of the liver. It contains within its layers blood vessels that supply the stomach and liver, as well as ducts which convey the exocrine secretions of the liver to the duodenum.
hepato = related to the liver; gastric = related to the stomach; the hepatogastric ligament is named according to its attachments
hepato = related to the liver; duodenal = related to the duodenum; hepatoduodenal ligament is also named according to its attachments

away from the liver and identify the falciform      ligament     , which is a remnant of the ventral mesentery that attaches the liver to the underside of the diaphragm and to the anterior abdominal wall as far inferiorly as the umbilicus.
in the shape of a sickle; crescent-shaped
ligament, in the context of the peritoneal cavity, refers to small mesenteries that extend between organs or from organs to the body wall
